                                         "PostMention":  "."
                                     },
                                     {
                                         "text":  "<h4>Longitude</h4>In mathematics, longitude (<b>θ</b>) s expressed in values ranging from 0 to 2π radians or 0 to 360 degrees. When applied to geographic coordinates, the Earth is divided into two regions of 180 degrees each. The dividing line between these regions is the <b>Greenwich Meridian line</b>, established arbitrarily in <htdate0> as zero degrees at the Royal Observatory in Greenwich, England. Positions east of Greenwich are measured as X degrees <b>East</b>, and positions to the west as X degrees <b>West</b>",
                                         "source":  [
                                                        {
                                                            "type":  1,
                                                            "uuid":  "006b21c9-6800-4deb-bb3f-a367dd38b703",
                                                            "text":  "NOAA",
                                                            "page":  "Longitude",
                                                            "date_time":  {
                                                                              "type":  "gregory",
                                                                              "year":  "2024",
                                                                              "month":  "06",
                                                                              "day":  "16"
                                                                          }
                                                        }
                                                    ],
                                         "date_time":  null,
                                         "isTable":  false,
                                         "imgdesc":  "",
                                         "format":  "html",
                                         "PostMention":  "."
                                     },
                                     {
                                         "text":  "<h4>Latitude</h4>Latitude (<b>ϕ</b>) is represented mathematically with values ranging from 0 to π/2 radians or from 0 to 180 degrees. In geographic terms, Earth is divided into two 90 degrees regions: the Northern Hemisphere and the Southern Hemisphere. In mathematics, however, positions south of the Equator are represented with negative values. Unlike longitude, which is measured from a prime meridian, latitude is measured from the Equator — an imaginary line dividing the planet into northern and southern halves. Positions north of the Equator are noted as \"X degrees <b>North</b>\", and those south as \"X degrees <b>South</b>\"",
                                         "source":  [
                                                        {
                                                            "type":  1,
                                                            "uuid":  "72ea1365-bb46-4036-a9e2-7384896e0a28",
